{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491523"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"968"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/968"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.08,0.08,0.73,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"968"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/968"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"968"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75678"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"589"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31527"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with a three day history of foul-smelling vaginal discharge. Her last menstrual period was seven days ago. A speculum examination shows a creamy-grey discharge and a swab is taken for culture. The swab is smeared onto a slide for microscopy, which shows clue cells. The vaginal pH is 5.0 (range 4.0-4.5). A fishy odour is present on addition of 10% potassium hydroxide to the vaginal fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluconazole","Azithromycin","Doxycycline","Metronidazole","Acetic acid vaginal gel"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBacterial vaginosis is the most likely cause for this woman\u0027s presentation, and is supported by the findings of elevated vaginal pH, fishy odour, clue cells, and a creamy-grey discharge (the AMSEL criteria). Bacterial vaginosis occurs when there is an increase in anaerobic species (eg Gardnerella vaginalis) with simultaneous reduction in lactobacilli. The AMSEL criteria is met when at least 3 out of 4 of the following are present:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVaginal pH \u0026gt;4.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPresence of clue cells in vaginal fluid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMilky, homogenous vaginal fluid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERelease of amine (fishy) odour after addition of 10% potassium hydroxide to the vaginal fluid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe causative organisms in bacterial vaginosis are most likely to be sensitive to \u003Cstrong\u003Emetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metronidazole is the antibiotic of choice for bacterial vaginosis."],"references":["Hay P. Bacterial vaginosis. F1000Res. 2017; 6:1761.","Coudray MS, Madhivanan P. Bacterial vaginosis-A brief synopsis of the literature Eur J Obstet Gynecol Reprod Biol. 2020; 245:143-48."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75678"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"968"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75678"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T14:21:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-